{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393347387/1938030201/0028.xml":{"full_text":"Walter Wiitchell\nOn Broadway\n(Trado Mark Hegltteredj Copyright. li>3g i>aiiy Mirror, Ino.\nNew York Heartbeat\nFaces ABout Town: Hey wood Broun in the Chez Stork featuring\na new cravat with colors red and black The hues of the anarchist!\nHerbert Bayard Swope, the Economic Royalist, hastening for the\nmidnight piano to the Coast Insiders will bet you Swope won't be\nSenator, as he hopes Ben Hecht, who used to be a columnist him*\nt\u00b0 stay pretty, with his iodine painted conk\u2014to bring back\nhis hair, which, of course, it won\u2019t The Countess di Prasso against\nthe bar at \"21\u201d ta-ta\u2019ing everybody before riding the clouds to Palm\nSprings for a month Prancia White, the operaticanary, shivering\nin a huge hunk of mink in front of Carnegie Hall Frederic March,\ncaressed by the Bermuda sun and looking fitter, being worshiped by\nan unmarried girl of 10, who described him as \"delicious-looking\u201d\nCharles MacArthur shaking his head as he reads that Helen Hayes is\ndivorcing him, which she ain\u2019t The three sisters of King Zog, on\ntheir husband-shopping tour, who have orders to keep out of night\nclubs and the columns.\nSallies In Our Alley: Charles Martin, who distinguished himself\non the radio with his playlets, and now a Universal Picture addition,\nhas this counsel on why it is foolish to bet on horses. Too often, it\nisn t the horses who run the race\u2014but the gamblers Russ Morgan\novertieard this In a Broadway cinema cathedral: \u201cThe only good crack\nin the picture was when the film broke!\u201d Senora Bankhead stifled\nan actress who was knocking another player with: \"Oh, it\u2019s profes\nsional jealousy!\" To which Howard Dietz, the MGM press chief\nhere, added: \"Considering their combined talent\u2014it\u2019s amateur jealou\nsy\u201d Mme. Alma Clayburgh\u2019s definition of a good musician: When\nhe hears a lady singing in the bath\u2014he puts his ear to the keyhole.\nNew York Novelete: It was two years ago or so when he first signed\nwith a major Hollywood studio. Ho was hailed as one of the most\npromising bets for stardom. He has youth, looks, personality and\na grand voice Broadway liked him. He went over big in several\nBroadway lah-de-dahs and night spots\u2014and then the talent scouts\nfastened him to the Cinema City But that was two years ago\nAnd all of us wondered about him His name disappeared completely\nfrom the movie columns\u2014that\u2019s how forgotten he was Finally, the\nbig break came, and today he plays the romantic lead in the greatest\nbox office hit New York has had from Hollywood Yet, ironically,\nhe gets no screen advertising, billing or mention\u2014and isn\u2019t even seen\nin the picture! His name is Harry Stockwell\u2014the Prince Charming\nof \"Snow White.\u201d\nObservations: The unemployed dozing on the stairway inside the\nFifth Avenue Library The constant good humor of the traffic cop\nIn front of the Roxy Theatre The lady derelict in front of the\nGrand Central Depot reading The Mirror's column on beauty!\nThe razor blade salesmen around Times Square, whose real product is\na risgay booklet The bar on 83rd Street and Columbus Avenue\nwhere Evelyn Nesbit mournfully sings: \u201clrou Put Me on a Pedestal\nand Then You Tore Me Down\u201d The most perilous of the street\ncrossings: 59th Street and Columbus Circle, where the traffic comes\nfrom six directions! That woman with the white goose on a leash\nat midnight near 43rd and \u201cMain Street\u201d The movie theatre in\nthe Bronx which still advertises: \u201c100 Per Cent A11 Talkies\u201d The\nlady named Myles Standish of 63 East 91st St. The mailmen, who\nkeep their sacks in front of them while riding in elevators\u2014they must\nalways keep their mail in sight Mayor LaGuardia who smokes\n2-for-a-nickeI cigars, but gives his friends a brand that cost a dime\nThe Lady of the Evening who cruises the 40s\u2014in a taxi.\nMidtown Vignette: He is Broadway\u2019s most astonished citizen\nIt happened yesterday afternoon He is Sol, a youngster, who toils\nin the sandwlchette next door to the stare entrance of Loew\u2019s State\nTheatre He was picked up by the G-Whiz men because they caught\nhim talking to one of those German spies\u2014the bogey-men of the cur\nrent front-pages The funny part (but hardly to him) of Sol being\ntaken along with the Nazi snoopers is that he is even more Hebraic\nthan a Lou Holtz accent!\nSounds in the Night: At La Conga: \u201cHe\u2019d be a success if his\nbooks had half the circulation his wife has\u201d In the Garbo: \"lie\nwas introduced to me as a famous explorer, and bulccve me\u2014he cer\ntinny is!\u201d In Club 18: \u201cWhen she was young she played with\nJacks\u2014now she toys with Johns\u201d In the Queen Mary: \u201cFind out\nwho she is\u2014then find out who she thinks she is!\u201d In the Village\nBarn: \u201cI\u2019d even trust him with your wife\u201d In the Gay 90s: \u201cThey\nhave an estate at Newport, a villa at Cannes and a brother at Alca\ntraz\u201d In Bill Bcrtoiotti's: \"She\u2019s the kinria dame whose morals\narc always standing at attention\u201d In the Merry Go-Kouiul: \u201cHe\nhas everything Charlie McCarthy has\u2014except Bergen\u201d At Casa\nManana: \"Will you please get your opinions off my nerves?\u201d In\nDave's: \u201cA Somebody is a well-known Nobody\u201d In \u201c21\": \u201cHe\u2019s\na human toothache\u201d At Leon and Eddie's: \u201cI wouldn\u2019t trust him\nany more than Mussolini trusts Hitler\u201d At the Cotton Club: \u201cHe's\ntall, dark, handsome and a louse\u201d In the Versailles: \u201cHe\u2019s very\nDemocratic\u2014hates everybody\u201d In Lindy\u2019s: \u201cHer voice is just too,\ntoo, Andy Devine.\u201d\nNew Yorchids: \u201cThe Sally, Irene and Mary\u201d score by Bullock\nand Spina, not Gordon and Revel, who wrote but two of the tunes.\nOur most profound Japanesy apologies Deanna Durbin\u2019s next film,\n\"Mad About Music.\u201d destined for fame Julie Haydon's lovely make\nbelieving in \u201cShadow and Substance,\u201d a hit Marie-Eve, a petite\nthing, at Ruban Bleu (Blue Ribbon, toots) on 56th .V The wows of\nAbbott and Costello, who will repeat with a different routine at Casa\nManana Sunday midnight The sinful tones of Barbara Parks, a\nnewcomer from Chi. Attractive, loo Leo Reisman on WEAF Thurs\ndeh eves L. Prima\u2019s new nonsense: \u201cYeh, There Ain't No Moon\nlight Tonight\u2014 So What?\u201d \u201cDipper Mouth,\u201d Larry Clinton's new\nest killer-diller.\nMemos of a Midnighter: Jack Osterman starts contributing to\nthe E. Cantor air show next week Estelle W'inwood and Robert\nHenderson will do \"Merry Wives of Windsor\" in the Spring Kay\nBrown, of the Sciznick-International outfit found \u201cOn Borrowed\n'i.me\" a smash, and hasn\u2019t drawn a cent from Dwight Wiman, who\nis getting richer It costs thirty cents to print each copy of Life\nF. W. GRAND\nLEADER IN REAL VALUES\nPURE FOOD MARKET\n1*1 SOUTH MAIN ST\nWEDNESDAY THURS. SPECIALS\na PORK\nRIB Vfe W? W\nCORNED gg Jy JT\nfresh v g^yWffl\nPORK T g|\u00a3%\nSTEWING W\u00bb W W W\nBOILING gg E| E| E\nlb\nRIB LAMB CHOPS 2 lbs 29c\nCENTER CUT n\nPork Chops 15n\n(SKINLESS\nJ\u00a3rankfurtsjMU>\u00a3\nSHOULDER\nSTEAK \u2019sr ft\n(FANCY OPEN EYE\nSwiss Cheese ^Zy/\nGENUINE SPRING mm\nLamb Fores 14i\u00bb\nCAMPBELLS\nTOMATOO\nSOUP 0\n20\nERAVM-AMEtthJAH\nSPA\nQHETTI\nfeEA-SHEEl\n3 cans 25'\nMAINE\nCLAMS\ntall\n10\nJERSEY\nPORK\nBEANS\n21 ft 4 4\ncans I\nEAGLE BRAND\nMAINE A\nSARDINES canHc\nREE-'Mtl\nDesserts Qc\nFebruary\u2019s Building Permits Reach $55,400\nCheckup With 1937\u2019s\nRecord Of Activities\nImpresses Officials\nSix One=FamiIy Houses to Be Erected\u2014Factory Addi\ntions Add $13,000 to Month\u2019s Total\u2014Current\nYear Credited With Auspicious Start\nBuilding figures for February, as\nreleased today by Building Inspec\ntor Patrick J. Carlin, show that the\nmonth had a total of $55,400, only\nabout $5,000 under the correspond\ning month in 1937 which was the\nbest February since 1930.\nAll of this is to the effect that,\nin spite of the business recession\nTOASTMASTER\njohn f. mchonough\nJudge John F. McDonough will\nbe toastmaster at the St. Patrick\u2019s\nDay banquet of the Irish-Ameri\ncan Social club, in The Elton,\nMarch 13, President Hugh J. Mc\nGill announced today.\nFinal arrangements for the din\nner and dance were made at a\nmeeting of the committees in\ncharge at The Elton last night.\nThe dance will be held March 17\nat Buckingham hall.\nJAMES M\u2019CARTHY\nTAKEN BY DEATH\nNaugatuck Man Life Mem=\nber of Inter\u2019l Brick=\nlayers of America\nJames McCarthy, 84, died this\nmorning at the home of his daugh\nter, Mrs. Ingward Nissen of Theresa\nstreet, Naugatuck following a ling\nering illness.\nThe body was removed to the\nCarlson funeral home, 270 Church\nStreet, Naugatuck. Funeral arrange\nments are incomplete.\nBesides Mrs. Nissen he is survived\nby two other daughters, Mrs. Mary\nLouden of Wantagh, L. I., and Mrs.\nMary Mary Snyder of Flushing, L.\nI.; a son, Joseph McCarthy of Free\nport, L. I., three grandchildren and\na grandchild.\nMr. McCarthy was born in Man\nchester, England, becoming a citi\nzen in the United States at the age\nof 25. He resided in Freeport, L. I.\nfor a number of years and was a\nNaugatuck resident the past four\nyears.\nHe was a member of the Brick\nlayers Union, No. 4 of New York\nand only recently was given a Gold\nen Jubilee Life Membership in the\nBricklayers- Masons- Plasters Inter\nnational Union of America.\nMr. McCarthy participated in the\nconstruction of the Woolworth Tow\ner in New York City and was at\none time affiliated with the Stan\nford White architectural firm.\nFUNERALS\nThe funeral of Mrs. Catherine\nNeagle, widow of Garrett Neagle,\nwill be held tomorrow morning at\n8:15 o'clock from the home, 15\nMitchell avenue, to the church of\nthe Immaculate Conception, where\na solemn high mass will be cele\nbrated at 9 o'clock. Burial will be\nin old St. Joseph\u2019s cemetery.\nThe funeral of Mrs. Cecelia G.\nHoran will be held tomorrow morn\ning from the Mulville funeral home,\n270 West Main street, at 8:15\no\u2019clock to the church of SS. Peter\nand Paul where a solemn high mass\nwill be celebrated at 9 o'clock. Bur\nial will be in Calvary cemetery.\nPrivate funeral services for Mrs.\nFrederick Gould were held today\nat the Alderson funeral home, 70\nCentral avenue, Rev. Dr. John C.\nWalker, pastor of the Second Con\ngregational church, officiating. Bur\nial was in new Pine Grove cemetery.\nThe funeral of John Stokes will\nbe. held tomorrow morning from\nthe Mazalka funeral home, 10 Por\nter street, at 8:30 o\u2019clock to St.\nJoseph\u2019s church, where mass will\nbe celebrated at 9 o'clock. Burial\nwill be in the family plot, old St.\nJoseph\u2019s cemetery.\nThe funeral of Miss Margaret T.\nRyan of 195 North Main street will\nbe held tomorrow. Burial will be\nin St. Bernard's cemetery, Hazard\nville.\nIll 101)\n(HUFFIN' In this city, March 1st,\n1938, Mrs. Nora (Cooper) Oriffln,\nof 112 South St. Funeral Friday\nmorning, at 8:15 o\u2019clock, from Mill\nville Funeral Home. 27n West Main\nSt., to St. Francis Xavier\u2019s Church.\nBurial In Calvary cemetery.\nSHELLEY\u2014In this city, March 2nd.\n1938, Arthur Eugene Shelley, of 33\nClifton Ave. Frlvato funeral Thurs\nday from Alderson Funeral Home,\n70 Central Ave.\nKIEMH\u2014In this city, Mnreh 1st,\n1938, Mrs. Mary Kleins, 104 Peer!\nliiiko Rond. Funeral tomorrow af\nternoon, at 2:0U o\u2019clock, from Lun\nny Funeral Home, 25 Central Ave.\nBurial In Prospect cemetery.\nand employment situation, Water\nbury building shows promise of go\ning ahead of recent years, it was\nremarked. From early indications,\nbuilding officials expect a better\nthan normal program locally.\nOne-Family Houses\nDuring February there were per\nmits issued for 6 one-family dwel\nlings to cost $22,500, as against the\nFebruary, 1937, figure of 6 one\nfamily dwellings which cost $28,\n500; one two-family house last\nmonth, to cost $6,000, as against no\n2-family houses in February, 1937.\nHere are the figures for other\npermits issued last month: Four al\nterations to dwellings, $4,500; one\ngasoline and service station, $1,800;\ntwo stores or commercial buildings,\n$9,000; 12 alterations or additions to\nstores, $11,200; one poultry house,\n$400.\nFor February, 1937, the following\nadditional figures are offered:\nchurch alteration, $500; factory ad\nditions, $13,00; garage, $900; gaso\nline service stations, $6,800; store al\nterations, $8,550; roof signs, $1800.\nThese with the one-family dwelling\npermits totalled $60,600, or $5,200\nmore than the permits for last\nmonths\nJanuary Totals\nIn January, permits were issued\nfor building at an estimated cost of\n$38,650. Additionally, in February,\nthere were sign permits, as follows:\nLicenses renewed, $10; permits, $41;\ninspections, 80, for $80.\nWOOLLCOTT WINS\nAT CASTLETON, VT.\nCastleton, Vt., March 2\u2014(UP)\u2014\nAlexander Woollcott, author, actor\nand raconteur, was victor today in\nhis political debut.\nHe polled 320 votes to win a\ntown election. His lone opponent,\nEdward R. Clark, veteran physician,\nreceived 280 votes, but was assured\na post on the board when Carl S.\nCole resigned to accept another of\nfice.\nWoollcott was precluded from\ncampaigning by his appearance in\nthe broadway production of \u201cWine\nof Choice.\u201d\nCastleton, whose population is\n1794, is noted historically as the\nsite of Zadock Remington's Tavern,\nwhere Ethan Allen plotted the\ncapture of Ticonderoga.\nOBITUARY\nGIGUERE\u2014Henry J. Giguere, 70,\ndied yesterday afternoon at his\nhome in Bristol after a month's ill\nness.\nAmong his survivors is a sister,\nMrs. Mary Vanasse of this city.\nThe funeral will be held Friday\nmorning at St. Anne\u2019s church,\nBristol. Burial will be in new St.\nJoseph\u2019s cemetery, Bristol.\nZIEMS\u2014Mrs. Mary Ziems, 51,\nwife of William Ziems, died last\nnight at her home, 404 Pearl Lake\nroad, after a long illness. She was\nborn in Waterbury and had lived in\nthis city all her life.\nBesides her husband, she is sur\nvived by a son, Wiiliam Edward\nZiems; two daughters, Miss Doro\nthy Ziems of Waterbury and Mrs.\nLillian Burns of Cheshire, and two\nsisters, Mrs. Nellie Franks, of Wa\nterville, and Mrs. Edna Jenks, of\nLakeville; a brother, Albert Blakc\nman of this city, and a grandson.\nFuneral services will be held to\nmorrow afternoon at 2 o'clock at the\nArthur J. Lunny funeral home, 25\nCentral avenue, Rev. Dr. John N.\nLewis, officiating. Burial will be in\nProspect. Friends may call this af\nternoon and evening.\nGRIFFIN \u2014Mrs. Nora t cooper j\nGriffin, wife of Patrick J. Griffin, of\n112 South street, died last night at\nSt. Mary's hospital after a week\u2019s ill\nness. She was born in Ireland and\nhad resided in the Washington Hill\nsection of this city for 30 years. She\nwas a communicant of St. Francis\nXavier church and a member of the\nRosary Confraternity of that parish.\nBesides her husband, Mrs. Grif\nfin is survived by a daughter, Ag\nnes; a son, Edward; two sisters,\nMiss Margaret Cooper, of White\nPlains, N. Y.; Mrs. William Sulli\nvan, of this city, and a brother,\nPriv. Patrick Cooper, a member of\nthe Waterbury fire department.\nThe funeral will be held on Fri\nday morning at 8:15 o\u2019clock from\nI the Mulville funeral home, 270 West\nMain street to St. Francis Xavier\u2019s\nchurch where a solemn mass of re\ni quiem will be celebrated at 9 o\u2019clock,\ni Burial will be in Calvary cemetery.\nGOTTLIEB\u2014Mrs. Annie Gottlieb,\n77, widow of Morris Gottlieb, died\nlast evening at the Waterbury hos\npital. She was born in Poland and\nhad resided in Cincinnati, Ohio, for\nmany years before coming to this\ncity to live with her daughter, Mrs.\nSarah Knopp of 178 Plaza avenue,\na year ago.\nBesides her daughter, Mrs. Gott\nlieb is survived by four grand\nchildren and two great grand chil\ndren.\nThe funeral was held this after\nnoon at 2 o'clock at the Alderson\nfuneral home, 70 Central avenue,\nwitli Rabbi Maurice Sigmund offi\nciating. Burial was in Tifereh\nIsrael cemetery, Cincinnati.\nSHELLEY\u2014Arthur Eugene Shel\nley, 56, of 33 Clifton avenue died\nthis morning. He was born in this\ncity, the son of Theodore and Nel\nlie Munger Shelley.\nMr. Shelley is survived by two\nsisters, Mrs. Frederick Willets of\nthis city and Mrs. E. J. Shook of\nEast Hartford.\nPrivate funeral services will be\nheld at the Alderson funeral home,\n70 Central avenue on Thursday,\nRev. David P. Gaines officiating.\nThree From the Land of Zog\nKing Zog\u2019s three unmarried sis*\nters showed that Albanian royal\nty is really democratic by posing\nfor pictures enough to content\neven a cameraman. Here they\nare as they looked on their arrival\nin New York. Their names are\nleft to right) Ruhjie, Myzejen and\nMa.xhide\u2014last name Zogu\u2014and\ntheir ages in the same order are\nTIME EXPIRES ON\nPAYMENT OF TAX\nPenalty of $1 Added To\nmorrow to Delinquents\nOld-Age Assessment\nReceipts from payment of the old\nage assistance tax amounted to\nabout $110,000 today with until 9\no\u2019clock tonight remaining for pay\nment of the tax without the added\n$1 penalty, under the 30-day provi\nsion.\nNumerous payments have result\ned from persons discovering that\nthey could not obtain motor vehicle\nregistration unless their taxes were\npaid, it was reported. Further, the\napplications for abatement because\nunemployment compensation checks\nhave not arrived on schedule, fail\nto relieve the payee from the $1\npenalty which goes into effect to\nmorrow.\nOnly those persons on full relief\narc able to obtain abatements and\nothers of the almost 1,000 persons\nwho have sought such considera\ntion will be liable for the $1 added\npenalty if, after investigation, they\nare found able to pay the tax.\nThe first list contained 55,000\nnames of persons subject to the\ntax but some revision will result in\ncutting this number by several\nthousand, it was reported.\nSHELL EXPLODES;\nWOMAN IS HURT\nBridgeport, Conn.. March 2.\ntUP) Struck by fragments of a j\nshell when a cartridge loading ma-\nchine exploded at the Remington I\nArms Co., Rimfire plant, Alice Lane,\n37, was under treatment at a hos-\npital today for severe burns on her\narms and face.\nFour other women were injured in\nthe blast, none of them seriously\nThey were working on shell shakers, j\ncontaining thousands of cartridges\nwhen the mishap occurred late yes-\nterday.\n\u2022AUI) OF THANKS\nWe wish to thunk our many\nrelatives, friends and neighbors,\nespecially the Water and Kngineer-\nIng Departments of the City of Wa\nterbary. the .Sisters and Alumnae I\nof .St. Mary's Hospital, the Nurses j\nof Charlotte llungerford Hospital,\nfor tlie many acts of kindness show*1\nus during our recent bereavement,\nthe death of our beloved husbur.o\nand father, Patrick II. Danalicr.\n(Signed)\nThe DANAHKK FAMILY.\nECONOMICAL\nRELIABLE\nThe Bergin\nFuneral Home\n290 EAST MAIN ST.\nDIAL 3-0683\nThe Funeral Service\u2014\nWhere Shall It Be Held?\nThe home for the services offer*,\nprivacy ami surroundings\ndated ullh the departed loved\none. The church afford* larger\naccommodations and the ntniOH\nphere of spiritual faith and com\nfort. The funeral home ha* many\nof the advantages of these fan\nplus the greater efficiency and\ncomfort of an establishment de\nsigned for the purpose.\nARTHUR J. LUNNY\n25 CENTRAL AVENUE\nPhonr 5-0189\nCOMPLETE FUNL.RALS\nI\nJ. H. MULVILLIj\nFUNERAL HOME\n270 W. MAIN ST.\nat\nHolmes Avenue\nDial 3-4131\nSisters of Albanian\nKing, in U. S., Deny\nRomantic Quest\n27, 30 and 25. Through an inter\npreter, they denied reports from\nAlbania that one of the objec\ntives in their American trip was\na quest for husbands. Without\nhaving set foot on shore, the\nPrincesses issued a statement de\nscribing America as \u201cwonderful.\u201d\nIn Albania, they are their coun\ntry\u2019s premier Girl Scouts.\nBehind The\nLines\nFlorio Post\nPlorio Post, No. 4, Italian\nAmerican World War Veterans of\nthe U. S., will entertain at the\nLibertay hall tomorrow night. All\nmembers of the Post and its\nAuxiliary may invite as many\nfriends as they wish.\nMoving pictures of the Ameri\ncan Legion National Convention\nwill be shown as well as some\npictures taken in Italy by Dr.\nThomas Cottiero. Dr. Cottiero\nwill show the pictures which he\ntook while in Italy on his recent\ntrip.\nWilliam T. Farrington, com\nmander of Corp. Coyle post, No.\n1, American Legion has been in\nvited to attend the event.\nMichael Di Primio, senior vice\ncommander is chairman of the\narrangement committee.\nHe is also chairman of the ar\nrangement committee for the an\nnual entertainment being held on\nMarch 20th at the Turner\u2019s hall,\nNorth Main street, on March\n20th. when Florio Post and its\nAuxiliary will be hosts to visiting\nofficers and members of the Na\ntional and State'Department and\nfrom the various posts and their\nauxiliaries from throughout the\nstate.\nMUSSOLINI TO PAY\nD\u2019ANNUNZIO HONOR\nLeads Pilgrimage to Gar=\ndone\u2014Famous Italian\nDied Yesterday\nGardone, Italy, March 2.\u2014(UP).\u2014\nPremier Benito Mussolini and a stall\nof his aides led a pilgrimage to\nGardone today to honor Gabriel D'\nAnnunzio, soldier, poet, dramatis\nand lover, who lay in state in the\n\u201cworld disgust\u201d room of his famous\nvilla.\nHe died last night in his bedroom\nof a brain hemorrhage. He did not\ndie the glorious death he had court\ned\u2014he had even talked of dissolving\nhimself in an acid bath. He died in\nflannel pajamas while dressing for\ndinner.\nToday the entire country honored\nhim as he lay on his bier at his\nvilla, wearing the uniform of a gen\neral of the air force. His body had\nbeen transferred from the \u201cieper's\ncell\u201d room of the villa to the \u201cworld\ndisgust\u201d room this morning.\nParis has denied the request to\nmake all public busses one class, in\nstead of first and second class as\nat present, yet of 283 new busses just\nput into service only nine have first\nclass seats.\nCHAMEBRS READ\nFOR GRAND JURY\nSessions to Be Staged\nWithout \u2018Benefit of Audi*\nence\u2019 Hearing Tuesday\nThe third floor chambers of the\nlocal County Court House, were In\nreadiness today for the occupation\nof the extraordinary grand jury,\nwhich will be convened there next\nTuesday morning at 10 o\u2019clock.\nIn less exciting days, the room Is\nused for overflow cases of the court\nof common pleas. Yesterday and\ntoday, however, all extra cases of\nthat court were tried in chambers of\nJudge Edward J. Finn.\nIt was officially learned that tha\ncourt of common pleas will not seek\nuse of the room again until sucft\ntime as the grand jury has com\npleted its investigations and deliber\nations.\nCounty Commisioner Jacob D.\nWalter said today that he knows of\nno alterations or special changes to\nbe made to the room 1 ecause of the\nentry of such an it/ \u00abortant group\nas the grand jury/ The room la\nconsiderably smallj/ nan the court\nrooms of the first/ 1 second floors,\nin that it contai/ no special seat\ning arrangemeiy .or an audience.\nAs no person o, c than the Jurors\nand witnesses will be allowed into\nthe room during the investigation,\nsuch facilities are not necessary.\nDROP IN LIQUOR\nREVENUE SHARP\nDecrease Last Month Is\nPartly Blamed on Busi=\nness Conditions\nRevenue received by the state from\ntaxes on liquor decreased sharply\nin February, says Tax Commission\ner William H. Hackett In hia\nmonthly report. Tax revenue from\nthis source in February, which rep\nresent.. taxes on liquor sold by\nwholesalers in January, amounted to\n$118 980.79. This compares with a\ntotal of $312,179 collected in January\nin the form of taxes for liquor sold\nin December.\nDecline in liquor purchases after\nthe holiday season and the general\nbusiness recession arc blamed for the\ndrop in state liquor taxes. This is\nthe first time since last July that\nliquor tax receipts have gone under\nthe $250,000 mark.\nOn the other hand, receipts from\nthe cigarette tax continued their\nsteady rise, totaling $143,200.59. This\ncompares with a total of $130,000 for\nthe month of January.\nRevenue from the state cigarette\ntax has increased regularly since last\nJuly. It is still somewhat less than\nnormal, however, since many dealers\nbo'uglu abnormally large supplies of\ntax stamps last May and June, so\nthey would have the stamps on hand\nbefore the law which reduced their\ndiscount rate went into effect on\nJuly 1.\nHampson, Mintie, Abbott\nFor Tired Rooms\nWe prescribe a breath of spring\nin the guise of bright new\nSlip Covers\nMade to fit like upholstery\nSofa, two chairs, five cushions\n$34^ net\nIntroducing the new \u201cBankmore\u201d design, on backgrounds\nof gold, blue, brown, green and woodrose. This fabric is a\nheavy crash. Also plain chevron cloths as companion cov\ners.\nThey\u2019re the kind of slip covers you\u2019ll want to keep on all\nyear round: Designs are matched perfectly. And they\u2019re all\nfinished off with box pleat valances on four sides.\n50 inch sateen lined draperies to match Bankmore design\n\u2022$5.95 pair.\nBUY ON OUR CLUB PLAN\nSSS=SSS9S9S=^BSa=S9S^\nHampson, Mintie, Abbott, Inc.\n91-99 WEST MAIN STREET WATERBURY, CONN.","height":"28196","width":"20664"}}
